        <section class="mb-16">
          <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Finance Structures for Trucks</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Chattel mortgage is the most common structure for owner-operators buying a truck outright — you own it, claim GST, deduct interest, and depreciate the asset. Hire purchase suits operators who prefer to spread GST payments over the term. Finance lease is popular for fleets where the operator wants to upgrade regularly without the hassle of selling. Operating lease or rental works for short-term projects or when you need a specific truck type temporarily.</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">For prime movers and high-value trucks, many operators set a balloon/residual of 20–30% to keep monthly repayments manageable. On a $300,000 Kenworth with a 30% residual ($90,000), monthly repayments over 5 years at 6.5% are approximately $4,108 — compared to $5,872 with no residual. The $90,000 is due at the end of year 5, at which point you can pay it out, refinance, or trade up.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-16">
          <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Why Use Nik Finance for Truck Finance?</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">The truck finance market is more specialised than the car loan market. Not all lenders finance heavy vehicles, and those that do have widely varying criteria for truck age, make, GVM, and operator experience. Nik Finance has access to 130+ lenders including specialist commercial vehicle finance providers who understand the trucking industry.</p>
